#+title:    Create a New Repository on Git
#+author:   h4ss4n
#+date:     2022-07-06 mie

* Using the Terminal

1. Open the terminal and enter the folder you want to create the repository.

2. Create the working directory.

   #+begin_src bash

        git init

   #+end_src

3. Add to the staging area.

   #+begin_src bash

        git add .

   #+end_src

   OR

   #+begin_src bash

        git add <file name>

   #+end_src

4. Commit to the local repository.

   #+begin_src bash

        git commit -m "first commit"

   #+end_src

   AND check for the changes.

   #+begin_src bash

        git status

   #+end_src

5. Force to move to a branch for future commit.

   #+begin_src bash

        git branch -M master

   #+end_src

6. Add the <name> to the local repository and the <link> to the remote repository.

   #+begin_src bash

        git remote add origin git@github.com:ShadowInSoul/OrgFiles.git

   #+end_src

7. Commit to the remote repository.

   #+begin_src bash

        git push -u origin master

   #+end_src

8. Create a new branch in your local repository (also in Github with the GUI).

   #+begin_src bash

        git checkout -b dev

   #+end_src

   AND check for the existing branches.

   #+begin_src bash

        git branch

   #+end_src

9. Add and commit from the dev branch before the push.

   #+begin_src bash

        git push --set-upstream origin dev

   #+end_src

10. Then push it normally.

    #+begin_src bash

        git push

    #+end_src

11. Check for changes in the dev branch on Github, also you can use the "Compare & pull request" to put up to date the Master branch.
